As a test sample, on the other hand, to be used after the GGSL-UNet has been trained to check the performance for application to real data, we will use the high-quality candidates of real strong gravitational lenses from the catalogs of (Petrillo etal., 2017, 2019a, 2019b) 222https://www.astro.rug.nl/lensesinkids/full_left.html and Li etal. (2020) derived from Fourth KiDS Data Release (DR4; Kuijken etal. 2019).
To select strong lens samples from KiDS, we follow two basic criteria. First, we keep the samples with the obvious structures of strong lensing cases, such as arcs or multiple images around the lens. Second, we select the cases matched with spectroscopic survey catalogs, such as SDSS (Bolton etal., 2012; Smee etal., 2013; Dawson etal., 2016), GAMA (Hill etal., 2011; Driver etal., 2011), and MUSE (Napolitano etal., 2020), which can provide precise spectroscopic redshifts (spec-z) for foreground galaxies. We finally identified 50 high-quality KiDS strong lens candidates, with their basic information shown in Table 1. This Table provides the \it BPZitalic_BPZ (Bentez, 2000, 2011) photometric redshift estimates based on 9-band (ugriZYJHKSsubscriptugriZYJHK_{S}italic_u italic_g italic_r italic_i italic_Z italic_Y italic_J italic_H italic_K start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_S end_POSTSUBSCRIPT) photometric data from KiDS+VIKING, derived using the Gaussian Aperture and Photometry (GAaP; Kuijken 2008) flux method. It also lists the spectroscopic redshifts (spec-z) of the 50 candidates, obtained by matching to different spectroscopic surveys, in Table 1. The details of strong lensing analysis for the 50 cases will be presented in another paper (Luo et al. in prep) in the future. Here, we focus on the decoupling and photo-z estimation of foreground galaxies and arcs from background sources in this paper.

The aperture magnitude of the foreground and background sources are approximately calculated following Eq. 17.
In Fig. 16, we plot the foreground and background magnitudes, mfsubscriptm_{f}italic_m start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_f end_POSTSUBSCRIPT and mbsubscriptm_{b}italic_m start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_b end_POSTSUBSCRIPT, which are calculated using the reconstructed optical band flux F^fsubscript^\hat{F}_{f}over^ start_ARG italic_F end_ARG start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_f end_POSTSUBSCRIPT and F^bsubscript^\hat{F}_{b}over^ start_ARG italic_F end_ARG start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_b end_POSTSUBSCRIPT, versus the KiDS catalog magnitude, MAG_GAaP in Table 1. Here, we have corrected mfsubscriptm_{f}italic_m start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_f end_POSTSUBSCRIPT and mbsubscriptm_{b}italic_m start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_b end_POSTSUBSCRIPT for extinction, as has already been done for the KiDS catalog magnitudes (MAG_GAaP, see Kuijken etal. 2019).
The mbsubscriptm_{b}italic_m start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_b end_POSTSUBSCRIPT is much larger than mfsubscriptm_{f}italic_m start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_f end_POSTSUBSCRIPT, as expected, since most of the lens candidates in the dataset have lower flux compared to the foreground galaxy.
Considering that the foreground flux is difficult to distinguish from the background and noise when the flux is low, we have additionally applied a correction for the foreground, using the flux inside the 95% flux contour of F^fsubscript^\hat{F}_{f}over^ start_ARG italic_F end_ARG start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_f end_POSTSUBSCRIPT. One would expect mfsubscriptm_{f}italic_m start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_f end_POSTSUBSCRIPT to approximate MAG_GAaP, but it is slightly larger in the uuitalic_u band.
As MAG_GAaP is derived from galaxy shapes and position angles, the GAaP method may not be able to distinguish between the lens and arcs in low SNR images, such as those in the uuitalic_u-band. Consequently, MAG_GAaP values for uuitalic_u-band images might include contributions from both the lens and the background galaxy.
Because the flux F^fsubscript^\hat{F}_{f}over^ start_ARG italic_F end_ARG start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_f end_POSTSUBSCRIPT only includes the flux of the foreground, we calculate the total flux of the foreground, F^fsubscript^\hat{F}_{f}over^ start_ARG italic_F end_ARG start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_f end_POSTSUBSCRIPT, and background, F^bsubscript^\hat{F}_{b}over^ start_ARG italic_F end_ARG start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_b end_POSTSUBSCRIPT. The magnitude is then calculated using Eq 17, and the results are shown in Fig. 17. The figure shows that the uuitalic_u-band matches better when considering both foreground and background flux, but the uuitalic_u-band magnitudes are still slightly overestimated in this case. Nonetheless, it demonstrates that the background image contributes a significant portion of the uuitalic_u-band flux. This is consistent with the physical scenario of the lens where the foreground galaxy is redder while the background is bluer.

Note that the flat priors in these training parameters of Table correspond to a flat prior to the colors, which we have deliberately chosen because we wanted the network to reconstruct the lens based on its geometry rather than use the color information. This will ensure no color biases are introduced in the reconstruction of different bands.

We can identify the following parameters: the radius RRitalic_R, from the center, (xl,yl)subscriptsubscript(x_{l},y_{l})( italic_x start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_l end_POSTSUBSCRIPT , italic_y start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_l end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ); the half-light radius, RhsubscriptR_{h}italic_R start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_h end_POSTSUBSCRIPT; the position angle, PAPAitalic_P italic_A; the Srsic index, nnitalic_n; the axis ratio, qqitalic_q. The parameters for the foreground and the background Srsic profiles are shown in Table 2. We used flat distributions for all parameters to avoid an unbalanced training sample and a realistic range of intrinsic parameters, as suggested from the real data (see, e.g., the BELL GALLERY, Shu etal. 2016).
As a first proof-of-concept test, in this paper, we cover a reasonable volume of the physical parameter space of the lensing systems, despite this might not fully consider all possible parameters, including extreme cases (for example, we are excluding very flat foreground systems with q0.20.3similar-to0.20.3q\sim 0.2-0.3italic_q  0.2 - 0.3). This option makes the network training more efficient, fast, and easier to converge while improving performance within the primary parameter space. Although the parameter space has been chosen to optimize the model training, the testing step in the following section shows that the GGSL-Unet still performs excellently in most mock/real lens test cases, as quantified by the chi-squares diagnostic.

where Esubscript\theta_{E}italic_ start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_E end_POSTSUBSCRIPT is the Einstein radius. The synthesis of the background galaxy will be sheared by large-scale external perturbations. This external shear is separated into two shear components, 1subscript1\gamma_{1}italic_ start_POSTSUBSCRIPT 1 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT and 2subscript2\gamma_{2}italic_ start_POSTSUBSCRIPT 2 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT, along the radial and tangential directions. In Table 2, we list the domain of these parameters in the bottom rows.
The foreground and distorted background images are then convolved with a Gaussian Point Spread Function (PSF). For the KiDS-like lensing systems, we have adopted a constant =0.4superscript0.4\sigma=0.4^{\prime\prime}italic_ = 0.4 start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT   end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT, corresponding to an FWHM 0.7similar-toabsentsuperscript0.7\sim 0.7^{\prime\prime} 0.7 start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT   end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT, which is the average seeing for the rritalic_r-band in KiDS and very close to the median seeing of the HQ strong lensing candidates in ggitalic_g- and iiitalic_i-band (0.8similar-toabsentsuperscript0.8\sim 0.8^{\prime\prime} 0.8 start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT   end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT)333To save computational resources and storage, we used the same mock parameters/templates across different bands, applying the same \sigmaitalic_ for all bands. For instance, we only mock 1x64x64 IfsubscriptI_{f}italic_I start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_f end_POSTSUBSCRIPT and IbsubscriptI_{b}italic_I start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_b end_POSTSUBSCRIPT with the PSF applied and then adjust the parameters \alphaitalic_, \betaitalic_, \gammaitalic_, and italic-\epsilonitalic_ to produce images for the four bands. This approach reduces storage and memory usage by 75%, which is beneficial when dealing with more bands (e.g., 9-band images) and large volumes of training data.. Note that for this first experiment, our choice to ignore the (albeit small) band-to-band seeing variation can potentially impact the accuracy of the GGSL-UNet in real applications where a band-to-band seeing variation might be rather common. As we will test the trained network on real observations in 2.2, we will keep this in mind as a possible source of systematics. However, we anticipate here that we will consider this implementation for future analyses (see 5).
The PSF and the lower limit of Esubscript\theta_{E}italic_ start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_E end_POSTSUBSCRIPT are driven to optimize the performances on ground-based observations.

The model is trained in batches, where the augmentation parameters are sampled from U(a,b)U(a,b)italic_U ( italic_a , italic_b ) (the first part of Table 2) to obtain Ff,Fb,FnsubscriptsubscriptsubscriptF_{f},F_{b},F_{n}italic_F start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_f end_POSTSUBSCRIPT , italic_F start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_b end_POSTSUBSCRIPT , italic_F start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_n end_POSTSUBSCRIPT, and FisubscriptF_{i}italic_F start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_i end_POSTSUBSCRIPT as the training targets. As discussed in 2.3, we have used online augmentation. This means the augmented training samples are constructed on the fly during training. For instance, this can include image rotating or zooming. Table 3:  U-Net architecture. The first two columns are the downsample block and the corresponding number of channels, while the last two columns are the upsample block and the corresponding number of channels.
DownBlock2D or UpBlock2D consists of two 2-dimensional convolution layers with skip connections. AttnDownBlock2D or AttnUpBlock2D consists of the transformer structure.

We use U-Net to extract the different components of lens images.
The U-Net model is a type of generative model consisting of two main branches: down-sampling and up-sampling blocks with shortcuts at the same level. The down-sampling and up-sampling blocks mainly comprise ResNet structure units (He etal., 2015) and transformer structure units (Vaswani etal., 2017).
The down-sampling reduces the dimension of features, while the up-sampling increases them. In our case, this means reducing the images last two dimensions (see Eq. 5). For instance, the first down-sampling block in Table 3 reduces the input image size from 46464464644\times 64\times 644  64  64 to 32323232323232\times 32\times 3232  32  32).
We use the Python module diffusers 444https://pypi.org/project/diffusers/ (von Platen etal., 2022) to quickly build a U-Net model, in which the blocks and the channels used are shown in Table 3.
